":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Lleucu","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Lucia</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lleucu II ferch Llewelyn was born in 1300, in Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Maredudd ab Owain. She died in Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1300–":"1300–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1314":"1314","1300":"1300","1270":"1270","Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1300–":"1300–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1314–Female":"1314–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1314":"1314","1300":"1300","1270":"1270","Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Cardiganshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1300–":"1300–Décédée","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1314–Female":"1314–Décédée","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1314":"1314","1300":"1300","1270":"1270","Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Cardiganshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Wales, United Kingdom":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lleucu II ferch Llewelyn est née en 1300, à Cardiganshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Maredudd ab Owain. Elle est décédée à Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1300–":"1300–Verstorben","1270–Male":"1270–Verstorben","1314–Female":"1314–Verstorben","1300–Female":"1300–Verstorben","1314":"1314","1300":"1300","1270":"1270","Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Lleucu II ferch Llewelyn wurde 1300 in Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mit Maredudd ab Owain mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb 